
1. What is REST API? Why is it stateless?
================================================================================
 -> REST API stands for Representational State Transfer Application Programming Interface.
 -> It is a way for client and server to communicate over HTTP using standard methods like:
    GET, POST, PUT, DELETE.
 -> It is stateless because the server does not store client session data, and each request
    contains all necessary information.
    
 2. Difference between REST and SOAP?
 ============================================================================
  -> Representational State Transfer
  -> Simple Object Access Protocol
  -> REST is a lightweight architectural style using HTTP and JSON.
  -> while SOAP is a protocol using XML with strict standards and strong built-in security.
  -> REST is faster and commonly used in modern applications, while SOAP is common in enterprise legacy systems.
  
 3. Difference between @Controller and @RestController?
 ===============================================================================
  -> @Controller is used for Spring MVC applications to return view pages, while @RestController is used for
     REST APIs and returns JSON/XML response directly. @RestController is a combination of @Controller and @ResponseBody
     
 4. Difference between GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE?
 ===============================================================================

	| Method | Purpose                      | CRUD Operation | Idempotent |
	| ------ | ---------------------------- | -------------- | ---------- |
	| GET    | Fetch data                   | Read           | ✅ Yes      |
	| POST   | Create new data              | Create         | ❌ No       |
	| PUT    | Full update existing data    | Update         | ✅ Yes      |
	| PATCH  | Partial update existing data | Update         | Usually ✅  |
	| DELETE | Remove data                  | Delete         | ✅ Yes      |
 
 5. Difference between PUT and PATCH?
 =================================================================================
  -> PUT is used for full replacement/update of a resource, while PATCH is used for partial update of specific fields only.
  
 6. What is idempotency? Which HTTP methods are idempotent?
 =================================================================================
 -> Idempotency means:
       If the same request is sent multiple times, but server give the same result at once.
       
		| Method  | Idempotent?          | Reason                        |
		| ------- | -------------------- | ----------------------------- |
		| GET     | ✅ Yes                | Only fetches data             |
		| PUT     | ✅ Yes                | Same update gives same result |
		| DELETE  | ✅ Yes                | After delete, still deleted   |
		| HEAD    | ✅ Yes                | Metadata only                 |
		| OPTIONS | ✅ Yes                | Checks allowed methods        |
		| PATCH   | ⚠️ Usually / depends | Based on implementation       |
		| POST    | ❌ No                 | Can create duplicates         |
		
